A node with no inner nodes, but inside self loops will have automatic layout applied to it. However, the standard `LayoutAlgorithmResolver` won't resolve a layout algorithm for such a node. Example:

```
node N1 {
	insideSelfLoops.activate: true
	port P1
	port P2
}

edge N1.P1 -> N1.P2 {
	insideSelfLoops.yo: true
}
```

Consider the following test:

```java
@ConfiguratorProvider
public LayoutConfigurator depthFirstConfigurator() {  /* ... */ }

@ConfiguratorProvider
public LayoutConfigurator greedyConfigurator() {  /* ... */ }

@ConfiguratorProvider
public LayoutConfigurator interactiveConfigurator()  {  /* ... */ }

@TestAfterProcessor(DepthFirstCycleBreaker.class)
@TestAfterProcessor(GreedyCycleBreaker.class)
@TestAfterProcessor(InteractiveCycleBreaker.class)
public void testDF(final Object graph) {
    testStuff(...)
}
```

The configuration methods configure the input graph for one of three possible cycle breakers. The test method wants to be run if either of the configurators is run. However, instead it does not seem to be fired at all, or at least JUnit does not mark it as having completed either successfully or not.

The expected behaviour would probably be to run the test method if either of the processors is executed and to record the result. If the method is run several times, failures should be accumulated.

